{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}} {{Infobox Stadium | name = Gradski vrt | nickname = ''(City Garden)'' | image = [[File:Stadion NK Osijek 2 rujna 2008.jpg|250px]] | fullname = Stadion Gradski vrt | location = [[Osijek]], [[Croatia]] | coordinates = {{coord|45|32|42|N|18|41| 45|E|region:HR_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1980 | renovated = 2005, 2010 | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = City of [[Osijek]] | operator = Športski objekti d.d. | surface = Grass | construction_cost = | architect = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | project_manager = | main_contractors = | former_names = | tenants = [[NK Osijek]] (1980–present) [[Croatian national football team]] (1996-present) | capacity = 18,856 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://stadiumdb.com/stadiums/cro/stadion_gradski_vrt_osijek|title=Stadion Gradski vrt – StadiumDB.com|website=stadiumdb.com}}</ref> | dimensions = 106x69 m | scoreboard = }}
'''Gradski vrt''' (''City Garden'') is a multi-use stadium in the [[Croatia]]n city of [[Osijek]]. It is home to two Croatian [[association football|football]] clubs, [[NK Osijek]] and Fortuna VNO Osijek.
It has a capacity of 18,856 (17,876 for seating and 980 for standing).
== History == Construction started in 1949, but works were stopped several times. The first match played on the ground of Gradski Vrt was played between [[NK Osijek]] and [[FK Sloboda Tuzla]] on 7 September 1958. In 1980, the stadium was officially opened.
In 1982, the record of stadium attendance was broken, on the football match between [[NK Osijek]] and [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]. At that match, there were 40,000 attendants. The result was 1–2.
In 1998 seats and reflectors were installed. In 2005, the stadium was renovated. Under the west stand, VIP rooms were set and the lodge was rearranged, adding 1,000 new seats. The athletics track was reconstructed, repainted from red to blue. After this renovation, the stadium has fulfilled [[UEFA]]'s stadium criteria. In the same year, the stadium was a part of [[Croatia]] and [[Hungary]]'s failed bid for the [[2012 European Football Championship]]. At that time a project of a new stadium with a larger capacity was presented.
In 2010, the stadium was again repaired: the pitch was relaid, fences were painted and the seats were numbered. The reason was a friendly match between [[Croatian national football team|Croatia]] and [[Wales national football team|Wales]], which was held on 23 May that year.
In May 2016, the stadium hosted the [[Croatian Football Cup|Croatian Cup]] final.
==Future== In April 2018, [[NK Osijek]] President Ivan Meštrović released a detailed structure design for the new stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nk-osijek.hr/vijesti/14949/prestali-smo-sanjati-poceli-smo-zivjeti/|title="PRESTALI SMO SANJATI, POČELI SMO ŽIVJETI!"|website=NK Osijek official website}}</ref> A new state of art stadium will be built at the Pampas neighbourhood in [[Osijek]] as a part of the new NK Osijek training centre. The capacity of the new stadium will be 12,000, with all of the seats covered. The stadium will be UEFA [[UEFA stadium categories|category four]] and is supposed to be finished in 2020. During the stadium construction, [[NK Osijek]] will play their home games at the current [[Gradski vrt]] stadium, which is in the future going to be used as the main stadium for the [[NK Osijek]] B squad.
